{
    "title": "risc vs cisc on arrays",
    "html": "<div class=\"markdown prose w-full break-words dark:prose-invert dark\"><p>Yes, I was referring to <strong>memory-to-register</strong> and <strong>memory-to-memory</strong> operations, which are common in <strong>CISC architectures</strong> but <strong>not in RISC</strong>. This is often done using <strong>offset memory addressing modes</strong> in CISC.</p><p>Now, letâ€™s look at <strong>how arrays are implemented in RISC, given that it strictly follows the Load-Store model</strong>.</p><hr><h2><strong>1. How Arrays Are Accessed in RISC</strong></h2><p>Since RISC doesnâ€™t allow direct <strong>memory-to-memory</strong> operations, arrays are accessed using:</p><ul><li><strong>Base + Offset Addressing</strong> (indexing)</li><li><strong>Explicit Load (<code>LOAD</code>) and Store (<code>STORE</code>) instructions</strong></li><li><strong>Pointer arithmetic using registers</strong></li></ul><h3><strong>Example: Accessing an Array in RISC</strong></h3><p>Consider this C code:</p><pre class=\"!overflow-visible\"><div class=\"contain-inline-size rounded-md border-[0.5px] border-token-border-medium relative bg-token-sidebar-surface-primary dark:bg-gray-950\"><div class=\"flex items-center text-token-text-secondary px-4 py-2 text-xs font-sans justify-between rounded-t-md h-9 bg-token-sidebar-surface-primary dark:bg-token-main-surface-secondary select-none\">c</div><div class=\"sticky top-9 md:top-[5.75rem]\"><div class=\"absolute bottom-0 right-2 flex h-9 items-center\"><div class=\"flex items-center rounded bg-token-sidebar-surface-primary px-2 font-sans text-xs text-token-text-secondary dark:bg-token-main-surface-secondary\"><span class=\"\" data-state=\"closed\"><button class=\"flex gap-1 items-center select-none px-4 py-1\" aria-label=\"Copy\"><svg width=\"24\" height=\"24\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" fill=\"none\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" class=\"icon-xs\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" clip-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M7 5C7 3.34315 8.34315 2 10 2H19C20.65